title: Added Xrm.Page API for Microsoft Dynamics CRM
body:
[Recreated pull request to collapse commits and comments.  This series of edits is Travis-build confirmed in my fork.]

I've been using some form of a TypeScript definition file for Microsoft Dynamics CRM for 2 years. In order to encourage more Dynamics CRM developers to seriously consider TypeScript as a preferable language to hook into its UI's extensibility model, I've completely done up these definition files from scratch, and liberally applied code documentation, which borrows heavily from the Microsoft's own API documentation, to ensure a high-quality experience. Once the pull is accepted, I'm ready to go-live with a blog posting at crmentropy.blogspot.com that highlights some of the conventions I've taken with the definition (particularly around the use of Generics).

Could someone please do a code review to spot any deficiencies or suboptimal use of TypeScript. I learned just enough to write these files, but I think I got full coverage with the tests. :)

- Find a better way to expose matcher functions to the global and other scopes

I also changed the test to do it like shown in the docs.

title: React.render() return value incorrect
body:
React.render does not return an element but a component. It's the `this` from the render callback:

> Instances of a React Component are created internally in React when rendering. These instances are reused in subsequent renders, and can be accessed in your component methods as this. The only way to get a handle to a React Component instance outside of React is by storing the return value of React.render. Inside other Components, you may use refs to achieve the same result.

http://facebook.github.io/react/docs/component-api.html

This particular pull request is probably not perfect (e.g. I don't know what to pass as the type parameter for state so I just set it to `void`). It does scratch my particular itch, though; calling `.setProps(..)` on the return value of `React.render(...)` is now possible.

Sorry if I misunderstood. By no means a react expert. Nor typescript, for that matter.

Cheers

(oh and sorry for the newline at the end I used github's web interface for this PR didn't know it would add that)

title: Fix async.d.ts each* signatures
body:
Sub-tasks:
1. Add generic ErrorCallback type
2. Rename AsyncIterator -> AsyncResultIterator
3. Add AsyncIterator as resultless iterator type
4. Change each, eachSeries, and eachLimit to use AsyncIterator, since the iterator callback returns nothing but an optional error (I tested this and no, they do not behave like map/mapSeries/mapLimit, even if you call them like that, which is what Ruby's Array does, e.g., `results = [1, 2, 3].each { |x| return x * 2 }`)
5. Rename AsyncMultipleResultsCallback -> AsyncResultsCallback
6. Rename AsyncSingleResultCallback -> AsyncResultCallback

5 and 6 are not bugfixes, as is 4, but they save space (and caolan's own async documentation doesn't suggest one wording over the other).

1. Enabled calling a component factory with no arguments, eg `MyComponent()` (first argument was required in the defs, so you had to do `MyComponent(null)` if you didn't want to pass anything in)
2. Added a convenience overload to `getDOMNode()`, with generic parameter of an element type, to cast the returned html element to a more specific type of `Element`, eg `HTMLInputElement`, `HTMLAnchorElement` etc.

title: Fix the params type in angular-ui-router
body:
The params type was updated in angular-ui.

See the API documentation here:
http://angular-ui.github.io/ui-router/site/#/api/ui.router.state.$stateProvider

It changed from an array to an object. I don't see a better way to express the type until TypeScript gets union types.

I also added a test for it.
